text: z Organic & Supramolecular Chemistry TMSCN-PhI(OAc)2 Promoted Synthesis of 3-Cyanophthalides from Phthalaldehydic Acids Bidhan Ghosh, Soumen Chakraborty, and Dipakranjan Mal*[a] Trimethylsilyl cyanide (TMSCN) in the presence of PhI(OAc)2 and .OEt2 in dichloromethane is shown to be effective for direct BF3 conversion of phthalaldehydic acids into 3-cyanophthalides at rt in good–excellent yields. A number of substituents in the substrates tolerate the reaction conditions. This method works well also with 2-formylbenzamides. The 3-cyanophthalides 1 are prominent synthetic equivalents of ortho-quinone dimethide 1,4-dipolar synthons[1] and have been well-established as donors for the Hauser annulation,[2] an anionic annulation of phthalides with Michael acceptors like acrylates, vinylic ketones and arynes. They are also useful as building blocks for the synthesis of natural products, namely, spermidine dihydronaph- thoquinones.[3] In general, 3-cyanophthalides 1 are prepared by functional group inter-conversions of 1,2-disubtituted benzene de- rivatives,[4] such as phthalaldehydic acids 2,[5] N,N-dialkyl 2-for- mylbenzamides 3,[6] alkyl 2-formylbenzoates 4,[7] and o-toluates 5[8] iso- cyanophthalides by triflic anhydride and 2,6-lutidine has been reported as a viable alternative to cyanophthalides 1.[9] How- ever, phthalaldehydic acids 2 and 2-formylbenzamides 3 are most frequently used among the five classes, since they are readily accessible by directed ortho metalations.[10]

The conversion of phthalaldehydic acids 3 to cyanoph- thalides 1 requires two steps. Their reaction with KCN in aq HCl solution at 0 8C furnishes cyanohydrins 6, treatment of which with Vilsmeier salt (oxalyl chloride and DMF) followed by pyri- dine gives cyanophthalides 1 in varying yields (Scheme 1).[5c] Cyclodehydration of the cyanohydrins 6 can also be achieved by reaction with DCC.[5e] Herein, we report a direct method for the conversion of phthalaldehydic acids 3 to 3-cyanophthalides 1 in a single operation in dichloromethane. It is based upon the combined use of TMSCN, PhI(OAC)2 and BF3 etherate. [a] B. Ghosh, S. Chakraborty, D. The chemistry of hypervalent iodine reagents has recently been very fascinating and many organic transformations are con- veniently performed in environmental benign conditions by the use of these reagents.[11] Prompted by the work[12] of Kita group and Xiong group that CN– ion can in situ be generated in an organic medium by the interaction of TMSCN and PhI (OAc)2, we undertook the present study. For the presumed for- mation of an appropriate electrophile i. e. oxocarbenium ion from phthalaldehydic acids, we considered the use of BF3 etherate in line with our previous studies[13] on reactivity of phthalaldehydic acids. The reaction was initially examined and optimized with parent phthalaldehydic acid 7. Although the first few attempts were unsuccessful, it soon became apparent that BF3 etherate is a must to drive the reaction With the above optimized conditions (Table 1), we explored the scope of the title reaction with a number of phthalaldehy- dic acids. As test cases, o-formylbenzamides 23 were subjected to treatment with a mixture of TMSCN, PhI(OAc)2 and BF3 etherate followed by dissolving in acetic acid. Quite expectedly, the re- actions provided the corresponding cyanophthalides 25 pre- sumably via intermediates 24 (Scheme 3). Scheme 3. 3-Cyanophthalides from 2-formylbenzamides.. The following electron-arrow mechanism may be put for- ward to explain the formation of the cyanophthalides 1 (Scheme 4). The interaction of TMSCN with PhI(OAc)2 produces Scheme 4. Mechanism of formation of 3-cyanophthalides. PhI(CN)2 which is a good source of cyanide anion in an organic medium. We presume this species reacts with a phthalaldehy- dic acid through OH functionality to form activated phthalide 33. BF3 assisted loss of PhIO from 34 generates oxocarbenium ion 35. Subsequently, the available cyanide anion attacks at C3 of 35 to furnish cyanophthalide 1. The support for the mecha- nism, in particular, the formation of the oxocarbenium ion can be drawn from the inertness of the nitro derivative 21, and the substrates 26, 27 and 29 (Figure 2). Quite interestingly, the re- actions afforded iodobenzene contrary to the expected iodo- sylbenzene as shown in Scheme 4. The Formation of iodo- benzene is accounted for by the oxidation of TMSCN by PhIO to cyanogen as proposed by Frohn et al (Scheme 5).[14] Scheme 5. Terminal redox reaction. Phthalaldehydic acid 31 was chosen as a substrate to find out if a 1,4-dimethoxybenzene nucleus interferes the present cyanation reaction. It has been reported by Kita et al that such a phenyl ether nucleus undergoes facile aromatic nucleophilic substitution reactions under the influence of hypervalent io- dine reagents. When phthalaldehydic acid 31 was submitted to the reaction with TMSCN with PhI(OAc)2, an intractable mixture of products was obtained. Such complicacies may be due to various hypervalent iodine induced nucleophilic substitution reactions.[15] In conclusion, we have developed a one-pot synthesis of 3-cya- nophthalides from phthalaldehydic acids by cyanation with PhI (OAc)2-TMSCN in an organic medium. This protocol is ex- tendable to 2-formylbenzamide precursors. The yields of the transformations are typically in the range of 63–94 %. Hexane wash of the crude mixtures often leads to the isolation of the solid products. A number of functional groups tolerate the re- action conditions.
